oduced into Britain by Scandinavian settlers before the Norman Conquest. As a modern given name, it was revived in the mid 19th century and has remained in use since."]},{"name":"Eirik","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Eirikr</i>, a compound of <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or <i>einn</i> ‘one, alone’) + <i>ríkr</i> ‘ruler’."]}]},{"name":"\"den","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄧, see   Deng  .","Chinese: possibly from the Romanization of certain Chinese personal names of some early Chinese immigrants in the US.","Origin undetermined. — Note: It is possible that in the population figure published by the US Census Bureau the Dutch case-inflected definite article <i>de</i> ‘the’, which forms first part of surnames such as   Den Bleyker   and   Den Boer  , is in some instances counted as an independent surname. Compare   Ten  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deng","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Dean ."]}]},{"name":"Helige\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an early medieval personal name, a derivative of <i>heilagr</i> ‘prosperous’. The popularity of the name greatly increased with the subsequent change in meaning of the vocabulary word to ‘blessed, holy’."],"variants":[{"name":"Helje","meanings":["From an early medieval personal name, a derivative of <i>heilagr</i> ‘prosperous’. The popularity of the name greatly increased with the subsequent change in meaning of the vocabulary word to ‘blessed, holy’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Erik \"den Helige\" Jedvardsson was born in 1156 as the son of Jedvard and Cecilia Svensdotter. He had at least 2 sons and 2 daughters with Kristina Björnsdotter. He died on 18 May 1160, in Uppsala, Sweden, at the age of 4, and was buried in Gamla Upsala, Uppsala, Sweden."},"et":{"1156–18 May 1160":"1156–18. mai 1160","1156–1160":"